  "learnings_before": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Valproate and carbamazepine are the most frequently prescribed first‑line AEDs for focal seizures in Ugandan children, selected for their low cost and >90 % availability in district pharmacies.  \n- Clinicians target weight‑based dosing: valproate 20–30 mg/kg/day (max ≈ 40 mg/kg) and carbamazepine 15–25 mg/kg/day (max ≈ 30 mg/kg); doses are increased by 10–20 % when current dosing is below the upper therapeutic limit and seizures persist.  \n- Before any dose change or drug switch, baseline safety labs must be normal (ALT/AST < 2× ULN, platelets > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within reference); abnormal results preclude valproate escalation.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, phenytoin, lamotrigine) are avoided in children with a history of drug‑induced rash or hepatic impairment; carbamazepine is deferred when liver enzymes are elevated.  \n- Levetiracetam is reserved for cases of valproate intolerance or failure because its higher cost (≈ $0.20–$0.30 per 100 mg) and limited stock (≈ 20‑30 % of pharmacies) make it a second‑line option.  \n- Phenobarbital is used only for refractory epilepsy or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable, with caution in spastic cerebral palsy due to sedation risk.  \n- Breakthrough seizures often coincide with intercurrent illness (e.g., respiratory infection, otitis media); clinicians first verify ≥ 80 % adherence and normal labs before altering therapy.  \n- Baclofen 5 mg twice daily is routinely maintained for spasticity and is not changed when AED regimens are adjusted.  \n- Antibiotics and ear‑drops are stopped once the infection resolves and are not included in the AED decision hierarchy.",
